There is also a hint of peach that gives it a more round flavor on the palate.  Even with this round note the wine still provides a briskness that is the hallmark for this cooler climate region.  Pair this wine with light salads, chicken or fish.

Tasting/other notes: The vineyards that produce grapes for this layered Rioja are 25-35 years old, leading for quite a bit of terroir.  This is evident on the nose where you can sense the vanilla notes after being aged for 20 months in French Oak barrels, of which 50% are new.  This wine spends a minimum of 2 years in the bottle prior to release to achieve its Reserva status.  Aromatic notes of black raspberry, forest floor, and cinnamon translate to the palate seamlessly while a medium-plus tannic structure dominates the finish.  Pair this with roasted lamb or pork for a dinner to remember.

Pair it with charcuterie, lamb, prime rib, and heavier styles of goat cheese.

Tasting/other notes: Flegenheimer Brothers, McLaren Vale, Out of the Park, Petite Sirah stains the glass on the pour with big concentration.  Plummy and dark fruit aromas are primary, followed by light vanilla and spice.  The entry on the palate is soft, then progresses to a great finish full of tannins and flavor.

Flegenheimer Brothers, McLaren Vale, Out of the Park, Shiraz has earthy and plummy notes on the front of the nose along with lighter oak influences, most likely due to the 12 months of aging in a combination of Neutral French and American oak barrels.  Softer on the palate with a well balanced acidity, nice structure with a fruity finish.

Aged in both stainless steel and American Oak, this is a California Chardonnay that has something for everyone.  Bright fruity and floral notes are followed up by a creamy texture that plays on the middle and back of the palate along with noticeable vanilla and baking spice flavors.  The finish is full, round, and rich.  Pair this with seafood, fettuccine alfredo, or any dish that requires cream and butter.

Normal description: BOUNDARY BREAKS OVID MED DRY RIESLING
Tasting/other notes: The glacial carvings that created the Finger Lakes of New York are also somewhat responsible for the suitable growing conditions of the Riesling grape varietal for which it is so well known.  The geological structure of this region allows for the mineral and light slate notes on this fruity and ever so slightly off-dry wine.  With its hint of residual sugar and its evident acidic structure, it provides an incredibly versatile flavor profile that goes with a multitude of foods.  Try pairing this wine with any type of spicy food to help offset the heat.

Tasting/other notes: Sauvignon Blanc is the only white varietal that is grown on this family operated estate.  It is one of the few wines that is aged in three seperate vessels; French Oak, Stainless Steel, and Concrete Eggs.  The collective theme continues on the palate, where 11 blended cuvees come together to produce notes of rich stone fruit, spice, a light floral quality, and only a soft hint of grapefruit.  The structure's main act is the bright acidity intertwined with a supporting role by the lush ripe melon finish.  This wine will pair with fresh fruit, light salads, or poultry.

Maison Gelas is about the glorious nature of the spirit in the bottle and not packaging.  Being 100% Folle Blanche Grapes is a beautiful rarity.  Wonderful apricot, nectarine and yeast shine.  That is followed by a delicate nature of the oak before being bottled at natural strength.  In a time of high priced aged spirit, Armagnac should be your next frontier to find incredible aged spirit at great prices.

Pairing ideas can include anything from roast pork, herbed chicken, or baked fish.
